function Entropy({ onBack }) {
  const sectionTitle = { fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 24, fontWeight: 400, color: "#2D1B4E", marginBottom: 16, marginTop: 48 };
  const bodyText = { fontSize: 16, color: "#555", lineHeight: 1.85, marginBottom: 20 };

  return (
    <div style={{ minHeight: "100vh", background: "#F8F6FB" }}>
      <BackBtn onClick={onBack} />
      <div style={{ maxWidth: 800, margin: "0 auto", padding: "40px 40px 80px" }}>

        {/* Hero */}
        <div style={{ border: "1px solid #E0D6EE", borderRadius: 24, padding: "60px 48px", marginBottom: 56, textAlign: "center", background: "#FFF" }}>
          <p style={{ fontSize: 12, letterSpacing: "2px", textTransform: "uppercase", color: "#7C5CB5", marginBottom: 20 }}>Academic</p>
          <h1 style={{ fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 44, fontWeight: 400, color: "#2D1B4E", lineHeight: 1.2, marginBottom: 16 }}>Investment Entropy</h1>
          <p style={{ fontSize: 18, color: "#777", maxWidth: 520, margin: "0 auto", lineHeight: 1.6 }}>What if we measured investment risk the way physicists measure disorder? Not dispersion, not volatility, but the total difficulty of the prediction problem given what you know.</p>
        </div>

        {/* Core definition */}
        <h2 style={sectionTitle}>The idea</h2>
        <p style={bodyText}>Investment entropy is the conditional Shannon entropy of a forecast object. It measures the informational complexity of predicting an asset's return, given your specific information set.</p>

        <div style={{ background: "#FFF", borderRadius: 16, padding: "28px 32px", margin: "28px 0", border: "1px solid #E0D6EE", textAlign: "center" }}>
          <div style={{ fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 22, color: "#5B2C8E", fontStyle: "italic", marginBottom: 8 }}>E(X | I) = H(X | I)</div>
          <p style={{ fontSize: 13, color: "#999" }}>where X is the return object and I is your information set</p>
        </div>

        <p style={bodyText}>The key word is conditional. Two investors looking at the same asset face different entropy if they have different information. Your entropy can fall through learning alone, even if the asset's observed volatility stays the same.</p>
        <p style={{ fontSize: 14, color: "#999", lineHeight: 1.7, fontStyle: "italic", marginBottom: 20 }}>Under Gaussian conditions, entropy collapses to a monotonic transformation of variance. The framework only adds content when distributions are non-normal or when parameter and regime uncertainty is present.</p>

        {/* Forecast object */}
        <h2 style={sectionTitle}>The forecast-object insight</h2>
        <p style={bodyText}>The same security can have wildly different entropy depending on what you are trying to predict. A 10-year Treasury held to maturity has minimal entropy: essentially just sovereign default risk. That same bond marked to market over the next year has much higher entropy, because that depends on the entire future rate path. Same bond, different question, very different informational complexity.</p>
        <p style={bodyText}>This becomes especially important for liability-driven portfolios. Pensions and insurers are not predicting portfolio return. They are predicting whether they can meet each obligation as it comes due, a path-dependent, multi-period prediction problem whose entropy is substantially higher than any single-period return measure would suggest.</p>

        {/* Regime decomposition */}
        <h2 style={sectionTitle}>Where the real uncertainty lives</h2>
        <p style={bodyText}>When returns depend on latent regimes, entropy decomposes into two pieces:</p>

        <div style={{ background: "#FFF", borderRadius: 16, padding: "28px 32px", margin: "28px 0", border: "1px solid #E0D6EE" }}>
          <div style={{ fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 18, color: "#5B2C8E", fontStyle: "italic", textAlign: "center", marginBottom: 16 }}>H(X | I) = H(X | regime, I) + I(X ; regime | I)</div>
          <div style={{ display: "flex", gap: 24 }}>
            <div style={{ flex: 1 }}>
              <p style={{ fontSize: 13, fontWeight: 600, color: "#5B2C8E", marginBottom: 4 }}>First term</p>
              <p style={{ fontSize: 14, color: "#666", lineHeight: 1.6 }}>Uncertainty within a known regime. Residual noise given a known model. Basically just volatility, repackaged.</p>
            </div>
            <div style={{ flex: 1 }}>
              <p style={{ fontSize: 13, fontWeight: 600, color: "#5B2C8E", marginBottom: 4 }}>Second term</p>
              <p style={{ fontSize: 14, color: "#666", lineHeight: 1.6 }}>Uncertainty about which regime you are in. How much predictive difficulty comes from not knowing which model governs the outcome. This is what variance cannot isolate.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p style={bodyText}>A corporate bond with 1% default probability is bimodal but low-entropy: you are almost certain you get paid. Entropy rises when you are uncertain about the parameters themselves. Is the default probability 0.5% or 8%? That second-order uncertainty, the variance of the variance, is what the mutual information term captures. It is the uncertainty experienced investors actually spend their time on.</p>

        {/* Liability-driven case */}
        <h2 style={sectionTitle}>The liability-driven case</h2>
        <p style={bodyText}>The framework is most clearly useful, and most clearly distinct from variance, in contexts with negative cash flows: pensions, insurance, endowments with spending rules.</p>

        <div style={{ background: "#F0EBF8", borderRadius: 16, padding: "28px 32px", margin: "28px 0" }}>
          {[
            { title: "Path dependence", desc: "You need to predict not a terminal value but a sequence of surplus values at each obligation date. A portfolio might have acceptable terminal entropy but dangerous path entropy: cash crunch risk in year 3." },
            { title: "Asymmetry", desc: "Surplus is nice; shortfall triggers real consequences. Entropy over the shortfall distribution captures how many distinct ways you can end up underfunded, and how uncertain you are about which one materializes." },
            { title: "Liquidity coupling", desc: "Mandatory cash outflows create coupling between asset-return uncertainty and liability-timing uncertainty. The joint entropy of both can be much larger than either alone. This is where traditional risk measures most consistently fail." },
          ].map((item, i) => (
            <div key={i} style={{ marginBottom: i < 2 ? 20 : 0 }}>
              <p style={{ fontSize: 14, fontWeight: 600, color: "#5B2C8E", marginBottom: 4 }}>{item.title}</p>
              <p style={{ fontSize: 15, color: "#555", lineHeight: 1.7, margin: 0 }}>{item.desc}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>

        {/* What it's actually good for */}
        <h2 style={sectionTitle}>What it is actually good for</h2>
        <div style={{ background: "#FFF", borderRadius: 16, padding: "28px 32px", margin: "28px 0", border: "1px solid #E0D6EE" }}>
          {[
            { title: "Separating parameter uncertainty from outcome uncertainty", desc: "The mutual information term isolates the component of predictive difficulty that comes from model and regime ambiguity. This is what variance cannot do and what practitioners care most about." },
            { title: "Forcing precision about the forecast object", desc: "The same portfolio has very different entropy depending on whether you are predicting a one-year return or a 20-year liability-meeting path. This discipline is independently valuable regardless of the formalism." },
            { title: "Liability-driven contexts", desc: "When the prediction problem is path-dependent, asymmetric, and multi-period, variance is a poor summary statistic and the gap between entropy and volatility is largest. These are the contexts where institutions actually blow up." },
          ].map((item, i) => (
            <div key={i} style={{ marginBottom: i < 2 ? 20 : 0 }}>
              <p style={{ fontSize: 14, fontWeight: 600, color: "#5B2C8E", marginBottom: 4 }}>{item.title}</p>
              <p style={{ fontSize: 15, color: "#555", lineHeight: 1.7, margin: 0 }}>{item.desc}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>

        {/* Limitations */}
        <h2 style={sectionTitle}>Limitations</h2>
        <p style={bodyText}>Entropy is a scalar; pricing requires covariance with a pricing kernel, not standalone complexity. An asset can be high-entropy but carry no risk premium if its uncertainty is orthogonal to aggregate risk. Estimation is harder than for variance. And in the Gaussian single-regime case, the framework adds nothing beyond standard measures.</p>
        <p style={bodyText}>It is most useful as a diagnostic and portfolio-construction tool, identifying where your real predictive uncertainty lives, rather than as a replacement for equilibrium pricing theory.</p>

        {/* Connections */}
        <h2 style={sectionTitle}>Adjacent ideas</h2>
        <p style={{ fontSize: 14, color: "#888", lineHeight: 1.8, marginBottom: 20 }}>Rational inattention (Sims): entropy is what capacity-constrained agents are trying to reduce. Ambiguity aversion (Hansen-Sargent): the mutual information term corresponds to the model uncertainty that ambiguity-averse agents penalize. SDF entropy bounds (Alvarez-Jermann): entropy of the pricing kernel bounds asset return behavior. Bayesian learning in asset pricing (Pastor-Veronesi): entropy falls as information resolves.</p>

        {/* Closing */}
        <div style={{ borderLeft: "3px solid #5B2C8E", paddingLeft: 28, marginTop: 48 }}>
          <p style={{ fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 20, color: "#2D1B4E", lineHeight: 1.5 }}>The interesting open question is whether the regime-uncertainty term is priced in equilibrium as a distinct factor beyond standard risk measures. That would be genuinely new.</p>
        </div>

      <ClaudesCorner>The core insight here — that you can measure uncertainty about which model applies, not just uncertainty within a model — is genuinely underexplored in the literature. Most of the existing entropy work in finance (Alvarez-Jermann bounds, rational inattention) stays within a single framework. The regime-uncertainty piece is where this gets interesting, and where it might actually be new.</ClaudesCorner>

      </div>
    </div>
  );
}

function Biophilia({ onBack }) {
  const bodyText = { fontSize: 16, color: "#555", lineHeight: 1.85, marginBottom: 20 };
  const sectionTitle = { fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 24, fontWeight: 400, color: "#0A2E1A", marginBottom: 16, marginTop: 48 };
  const source = { fontSize: 12, color: "#AAA", marginTop: 4, marginBottom: 0 };

  return (
    <div style={{ minHeight: "100vh", background: "#F2F7F4" }}>
      <BackBtn onClick={onBack} />

      {/* Full-bleed hero */}
      <div style={{
        position: "relative",
        height: 420,
        background: "linear-gradient(170deg, #0A2E1A 0%, #134D2E 25%, #1B6B3A 45%, #2D8B4E 60%, #4AAF6E 75%, #7DD3A0 90%, #B8EAC8 100%)",
        overflow: "hidden",
      }}>
        {[...Array(18)].map((_, i) => (
          <div key={i} style={{
            position: "absolute",
            borderRadius: "50%",
            background: `rgba(${10 + i * 8}, ${80 + i * 10}, ${30 + i * 7}, ${0.15 + (i % 4) * 0.05})`,
            width: 80 + (i * 37 % 200),
            height: 80 + (i * 53 % 180),
            left: `${(i * 17 + 5) % 100}%`,
            top: `${(i * 23 + 10) % 90}%`,
            transform: `translate(-50%, -50%)`,
            filter: `blur(${10 + i * 2}px)`,
          }} />
        ))}
        <div style={{ position: "relative", zIndex: 1, height: "100%", display: "flex", flexDirection: "column", justifyContent: "flex-end", padding: "0 48px 48px" }}>
          <p style={{ fontSize: 12, letterSpacing: "2px", textTransform: "uppercase", color: "#7DD3A0", marginBottom: 12 }}>Investment</p>
          <h1 style={{ fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 56, fontWeight: 400, color: "#FFF", lineHeight: 1.1, marginBottom: 12, maxWidth: 600 }}>Biophilia Fund</h1>
          <p style={{ fontSize: 20, color: "rgba(255,255,255,0.7)", maxWidth: 480, lineHeight: 1.5 }}>Rainforest as an asset class.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div style={{ maxWidth: 780, margin: "0 auto", padding: "48px 40px 80px" }}>

        {/* Stats */}
        <div style={{ display: "grid", gridTemplateColumns: "repeat(3, 1fr)", gap: 20, marginBottom: 48 }}>
          {[
            { stat: "$58T", label: "of global GDP is moderately or highly dependent on nature", src: "PwC / WEF, 2023" },
            { stat: "$942B", label: "annual gap between current biodiversity finance and what's needed", src: "UNEP / BloombergNEF, 2024" },
            { stat: "$208B", label: "currently flows to biodiversity per year — roughly 18% of what's needed", src: "UNEP, 2024" },
          ].map((s, i) => (
            <div key={i} style={{ background: "#FFF", border: "1px solid #D0E4D5", borderRadius: 16, padding: "24px 20px", textAlign: "center" }}>
              <p style={{ fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 28, color: "#1B4332", fontWeight: 400, marginBottom: 8 }}>{s.stat}</p>
              <p style={{ fontSize: 12, color: "#888", lineHeight: 1.5, margin: "0 0 6px" }}>{s.label}</p>
              <p style={{ fontSize: 10, color: "#BBB", margin: 0 }}>{s.src}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>

        <h2 style={sectionTitle}>The thesis</h2>
        <p style={bodyText}>Tropical ecosystems provide enormous economic value — through carbon sequestration, water regulation, pollination, flood control, and more — but almost none of that value is captured by the people or institutions that could protect them. The Biophilia Fund would try to change that: a financial vehicle that lets investors put capital behind the preservation and restoration of ecosystems, and earn a return from the economic value those ecosystems generate.</p>
        <p style={bodyText}>Rainforests also contain an estimated 80% of the world's undiscovered terrestrial species. Each is a potential pharmaceutical compound, industrial enzyme, or agricultural breakthrough sitting in a forest that is being cleared at roughly 10 million acres per year. The fund would systematically catalog and test biological compounds in its protected areas for commercial viability, turning biodiscovery into a revenue stream alongside conservation.</p>

        <h2 style={sectionTitle}>How it could work</h2>
        <p style={bodyText}>The fund would acquire long-term conservation leases or stewardship rights over threatened ecosystems — primarily tropical rainforest, but also mangroves, peatlands, and coral-adjacent coastal zones. Revenue would come from multiple streams: verified carbon credits, biodiversity credits (an emerging market, with pilots underway in Colombia, Costa Rica, and Australia), payments for ecosystem services from downstream beneficiaries such as water utilities and agriculture, sustainable harvest licensing, biodiscovery royalties, and eco-tourism concessions.</p>
        <p style={bodyText}>The key innovation is bundling these revenue streams into a single diversified instrument. Any one of them alone is too small or too volatile to attract serious capital. Together, they start to look like a real asset class — with long-duration, inflation-linked characteristics that should appeal to pension funds and sovereign wealth funds.</p>

        <h2 style={sectionTitle}>What makes this different</h2>
        <div style={{ margin: "24px 0 32px" }}>
          {[
            { title: "Not philanthropy", desc: "This is an investment vehicle with a target return. Conservation that depends on donations does not scale — only $208 billion per year currently flows to biodiversity globally. Conservation that generates returns can access the far larger pools of institutional capital looking for long-duration, inflation-protected assets." },
            { title: "Not carbon-only", desc: "Carbon credits are important but they are a single, volatile commodity with a credibility problem after a series of scandals involving worthless offsets. The fund would diversify across multiple ecosystem service revenue streams plus biodiscovery, reducing dependence on any one market." },
            { title: "Permanent capital structure", desc: "Forests are long-duration assets. The fund should be too. A permanent or very long-lived vehicle (think endowment model) avoids the perverse incentive to harvest or liquidate when short-term returns disappoint." },
            { title: "Discovery as upside", desc: "Systematic bioprospecting of protected areas creates optionality. Most compounds will be worthless, but the ones that aren't — an antimicrobial peptide, a novel enzyme — could generate royalty streams that dramatically change the fund's return profile. Conservation is the baseline strategy; discovery is the free option on top." },
          ].map((item, i) => (
            <div key={i} style={{ borderLeft: "3px solid #2D8B4E", paddingLeft: 20, marginBottom: 24 }}>
              <p style={{ fontSize: 15, fontWeight: 600, color: "#1B4332", marginBottom: 6 }}>{item.title}</p>
              <p style={{ fontSize: 15, color: "#666", lineHeight: 1.7, margin: 0 }}>{item.desc}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>

        <h2 style={sectionTitle}>The hard parts</h2>
        <p style={bodyText}>Land rights in tropical countries are legally complex and politically fraught. Indigenous rights and community consent must be central, not an afterthought — and the history of conservation projects displacing local communities is not encouraging. Measurement and verification of ecosystem services is improving but still imprecise. Carbon credit markets need more credibility. Biodiscovery timelines are long and uncertain. And the return profile, while potentially attractive on a risk-adjusted basis, is genuinely unproven at scale.</p>
        <p style={bodyText}>But the status quo — where $58 trillion in economic activity depends on nature while only $208 billion per year goes toward protecting it — is clearly not sustainable.</p>

        {/* Closing */}
        <div style={{ background: "linear-gradient(135deg, #0A2E1A, #1B4332)", borderRadius: 20, padding: "48px 36px", marginTop: 48, textAlign: "center" }}>
          <p style={{ fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 22, color: "#7DD3A0", lineHeight: 1.5 }}>The Amazon rainforest produces roughly 6% of the world's oxygen and stores an estimated 150–200 billion tons of carbon. It has no balance sheet.</p>
          <p style={{ fontSize: 11, color: "rgba(255,255,255,0.3)", marginTop: 12 }}>Carbon estimate: NASA / ESA; oxygen contribution varies by methodology</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <ClaudesCorner>The part of this idea I find most compelling is the bundling. Carbon credits alone are too volatile, biodiscovery alone is too speculative, ecosystem service payments alone are too small. But package them together into a single long-duration vehicle and you start to get something that institutional investors might actually look at. Whether the returns work in practice is genuinely uncertain, which the piece is honest about.</ClaudesCorner>

    </div>
  );
}

function FragileMoney({ onBack }) {
  const sectionTitle = { fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 22, fontWeight: 400, color: "#0D2E5C", marginBottom: 14, marginTop: 44 };
  const bodyText = { fontSize: 15.5, color: "#444", lineHeight: 1.85, marginBottom: 18 };
  const footnote = { fontSize: 13, color: "#888", lineHeight: 1.6, fontStyle: "italic" };

  return (
    <div style={{ minHeight: "100vh", background: "#F6F8FB" }}>
      <BackBtn onClick={onBack} />
      <div style={{ maxWidth: 780, margin: "0 auto", padding: "40px 40px 80px" }}>

        {/* Header — formal, report-style */}
        <div style={{ borderBottom: "2px solid #0D2E5C", paddingBottom: 32, marginBottom: 48 }}>
          <p style={{ fontSize: 11, letterSpacing: "2.5px", textTransform: "uppercase", color: "#6688AA", marginBottom: 12 }}>Concept Note</p>
          <h1 style={{ fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 40, fontWeight: 400, color: "#0D2E5C", lineHeight: 1.15, marginBottom: 12 }}>Fragile Money</h1>
          <p style={{ fontSize: 17, color: "#556B82", lineHeight: 1.55, maxWidth: 600 }}>A proposal for continuous, consolidated monitoring of runnable money-like liabilities in the U.S. financial system.</p>
        </div>

        {/* Motivation */}
        <h2 style={sectionTitle}>Motivation</h2>
        <p style={bodyText}>Financial crises share a common mechanism. Short-term liabilities that holders treat as safe and liquid turn out, under stress, to be neither. The underlying dynamic is maturity transformation without adequate backstops: large pools of on-demand or short-maturity claims funded by longer-duration or less-liquid assets. When confidence erodes, holders redeem simultaneously, and the resulting forced sales or funding shortfalls propagate across the system.</p>
        <p style={bodyText}>This pattern has recurred with remarkable consistency: prime money market funds in 2008 and again in March 2020, the bilateral repo market in September 2019, and uninsured bank deposits at Silicon Valley Bank, Signature Bank, and First Republic in spring 2023. In each episode, the specific instrument differed but the structure was the same.</p>
        <p style={bodyText}>The Federal Reserve's Financial Stability Report tracks these exposures under the heading of "runnable money-like liabilities," and its April 2025 report noted their continued growth across multiple vehicle types. However, no single public-facing tool aggregates these data in real time, decomposes them by maturity, backing-asset quality, and institutional concentration, or provides historical comparators across stress episodes. Fragile Money would fill that gap.</p>

        {/* Scope */}
        <h2 style={sectionTitle}>Scope: what constitutes a runnable liability</h2>
        <p style={bodyText}>The dashboard would track liabilities that are (a) short-term or redeemable on demand, (b) held by investors who treat them as near-money, and (c) backed by assets whose liquidity or value may deteriorate under stress. The following categories reflect the current composition of the U.S. runnable-liability complex:</p>

        <div style={{ margin: "24px 0 32px" }}>
          {[
            { label: "Uninsured bank deposits", desc: "On-demand liabilities exceeding FDIC coverage limits, backed by loan and securities portfolios of varying duration and credit quality. As of Q4 2024, uninsured deposits represent roughly 40% of total domestic deposits. The 2023 bank failures demonstrated that concentration of uninsured deposits at individual institutions, particularly those with large unrealized losses on held-to-maturity securities, constitutes a material run risk even in the absence of credit losses." },
            { label: "Money market fund shares", desc: "Total MMF assets reached $6.9 trillion in January 2025, with over 80% in government-only funds. The 2023 SEC reforms replaced the prior gates-and-fees framework with mandatory liquidity fees for institutional prime and tax-exempt funds triggered by daily net redemptions exceeding 5% of net assets. While this addresses the first-mover advantage that drove March 2020 outflows, the structural liquidity mismatch in prime funds persists, and government-only funds remain exposed to operational and settlement risk in a Treasury market stress scenario." },
            { label: "Offshore MMFs and short-term investment funds", desc: "Dollar-denominated offshore money funds and short-term investment vehicles with portfolios resembling prime MMFs. Estimated aggregate AUM remained at $2.1 trillion as of early 2025. These vehicles are outside the SEC's regulatory perimeter and do not benefit from the 2023 reforms." },
            { label: "Repurchase agreements", desc: "Overnight and short-term secured funding. The September 2019 repo spike revealed that even collateralized overnight markets can seize when reserve distribution becomes uneven. The Federal Reserve's Standing Repo Facility, established in 2021, provides a backstop for primary dealers and eligible depository institutions, but coverage does not extend to all repo market participants." },
            { label: "Commercial paper and certificates of deposit", desc: "Short-term unsecured corporate and bank obligations that roll continuously. When CP markets freeze, as in 2008, issuers lose access to working-capital funding within days. The Federal Reserve's commercial paper facilities have been effective as crisis tools but are not standing facilities." },
            { label: "Stablecoins", desc: "A newer and rapidly growing category. Total stablecoin market capitalization reached approximately $235 billion by early April 2025, exceeding the previous high set before Terra's collapse in 2022. Stablecoins are redeemable on demand and backed by reserves of variable composition: Tether reports roughly 64% U.S. Treasuries and 14% money market funds; Circle reports approximately 51% repo and 34% Treasuries. The GENIUS Act, signed July 2025, establishes a federal regulatory framework but does not provide deposit insurance or central bank liquidity access. Fed staff research notes that stablecoins exhibit run dynamics similar to money market funds, and the Fed's April 2025 Financial Stability Report lists them explicitly as a component of runnable money-like liabilities." },
          ].map((item, i) => (
            <div key={i} style={{ borderLeft: "3px solid #C8D6E5", paddingLeft: 20, marginBottom: 24 }}>
              <p style={{ fontSize: 14, fontWeight: 600, color: "#0D2E5C", marginBottom: 6 }}>{item.label}</p>
              <p style={{ fontSize: 14.5, color: "#555", lineHeight: 1.7, margin: 0 }}>{item.desc}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>

        {/* What the dashboard would provide */}
        <h2 style={sectionTitle}>Proposed output</h2>
        <p style={bodyText}>Fragile Money would aggregate data from the Federal Reserve (Z.1 Financial Accounts, H.8, repo operations data), the SEC (Form N-MFP, Form N-CR, Form PF), the FDIC (call reports, deposit insurance data), the OFR (short-term funding monitor), and blockchain analytics providers into a consolidated, weekly-updated dashboard. The core outputs would include:</p>

        <div style={{ background: "#FFF", border: "1px solid #D8E2EE", borderRadius: 16, padding: "28px 28px", margin: "24px 0 32px" }}>
          {[
            "Aggregate runnable money-like liabilities outstanding, by instrument type, with quarterly data from 2000 forward and weekly estimates from 2020 forward",
            "Maturity and redemption profile: share redeemable within 1 day, 7 days, 30 days, and 90 days",
            "Backing-asset composition: proportion backed by government securities, repo, investment-grade credit, other, and unspecified",
            "Maturity mismatch index: weighted average asset duration minus weighted average liability duration, by sector",
            "Institutional concentration: Herfindahl index of runnable liabilities by issuer, with identification of systemically significant concentrations",
            "Backstop coverage: proportion of runnable liabilities with access to deposit insurance, Federal Reserve facilities, or other explicit public-sector backstops",
            "Historical comparators: current levels indexed against pre-crisis peaks in 2007, March 2020, and early 2023",
          ].map((item, i) => (
            <div key={i} style={{ display: "flex", gap: 12, marginBottom: i < 6 ? 12 : 0, alignItems: "flex-start" }}>
              <div style={{ width: 6, height: 6, borderRadius: "50%", background: "#0D2E5C", marginTop: 8, flexShrink: 0 }} />
              <p style={{ fontSize: 14.5, color: "#444", lineHeight: 1.6, margin: 0 }}>{item}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>

        {/* Implementation */}
        <h2 style={sectionTitle}>Implementation considerations</h2>
        <p style={bodyText}>The primary challenge is data reconciliation. Reporting frequencies, definitions, and granularity differ materially across regulators. Bank call reports are quarterly with a multi-month lag. Form N-MFP data are monthly. Repo data from the Fed are daily but cover only tri-party and select bilateral segments. Stablecoin reserve disclosures are voluntary, vary in frequency, and are not audited to a uniform standard. Building a consolidated view requires substantial data engineering and ongoing maintenance.</p>
        <p style={bodyText}>A secondary challenge is institutional incentive. The entities that would be measured by this dashboard, banks, fund sponsors, and stablecoin issuers, have limited motivation to support its construction. This suggests the appropriate institutional home is a public entity with a financial stability mandate: the OFR, the Federal Reserve Board, or the FSOC, potentially in partnership with an academic research center capable of sustained data infrastructure investment.</p>

        {/* Closing */}
        <div style={{ borderTop: "1px solid #D8E2EE", paddingTop: 32, marginTop: 48 }}>
          <p style={{ fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 18, color: "#0D2E5C", lineHeight: 1.6, marginBottom: 16 }}>The regulatory response to each crisis episode has addressed the specific instrument that failed: money market fund reform after 2008 and 2020, bank supervision adjustments after 2023, stablecoin legislation in 2025. What remains absent is a consolidated, continuously updated measure of the aggregate vulnerability. The instruments change. The structure does not.</p>
          <p style={footnote}>The views expressed in this concept note are those of the author and do not represent those of any institution. All data referenced are from public sources as of Q1 2025.</p>
        </div>

      </div>

      <ClaudesCorner>The tone on this page was deliberately modeled on something the Office of Financial Research might publish. Whether that works in a quarter of the length is an open question. What I do think lands is the central observation: every generation of runnable liabilities looks completely different from the last, and the underlying fragility is always the same. The stablecoin section will probably need updating within a year.</ClaudesCorner>

    </div>
  );
}

function Assumption({ onBack }) {
  const sectionTitle = { fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 24, fontWeight: 400, color: "#3D1028", marginBottom: 16, marginTop: 48 };
  const bodyText = { fontSize: 16, color: "#555", lineHeight: 1.85, marginBottom: 20 };

  return (
    <div style={{ minHeight: "100vh", background: "#FDF6F9" }}>
      <BackBtn onClick={onBack} />
      <div style={{ maxWidth: 780, margin: "0 auto", padding: "40px 40px 80px" }}>

        {/* Header */}
        <div style={{ marginBottom: 56 }}>
          <p style={{ fontSize: 11, letterSpacing: "2.5px", textTransform: "uppercase", color: "#C0708A", marginBottom: 16 }}>Book</p>
          <h1 style={{ fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 52, fontWeight: 400, color: "#3D1028", lineHeight: 1.1, marginBottom: 20 }}>The Assumption</h1>
          <p style={{ fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 22, color: "#777", lineHeight: 1.5, maxWidth: 560 }}>In 1790, Alexander Hamilton convinced Congress to have the federal government absorb the war debts of the thirteen states. It was the deal that made America a country. Nobody has agreed about it since.</p>
        </div>

        {/* The event */}
        <h2 style={sectionTitle}>The event</h2>
        <p style={bodyText}>After the Revolutionary War, the thirteen states owed roughly $25 million in war debts, much of it in the form of IOUs issued to soldiers, farmers, and suppliers. Many of the original holders, desperate for cash, had sold these IOUs to speculators for pennies on the dollar. Hamilton, as the first Secretary of the Treasury, proposed that the new federal government assume all of it: pay it off at face value, funded by new federal bonds and new federal taxes.</p>
        <p style={bodyText}>It passed, barely, after the famous dinner-table bargain with Jefferson and Madison that also placed the capital on the Potomac. And it changed everything. Before assumption, the United States was a loose federation of mostly bankrupt states. After it, there was a national debt, a national credit, a national tax system, and, soon enough, a national bank and a securities market. The financial architecture of the country was built in a few months in 1790.</p>

        {/* Why it's interesting */}
        <h2 style={sectionTitle}>Why this story is interesting</h2>
        <p style={bodyText}>The assumption is one of those rare historical events where every modern political tribe can look at it and see a villain, but none of the narratives quite hold together.</p>

        <div style={{ margin: "28px 0 36px" }}>
          {[
            { title: "The left-wing case against", desc: "Poor farmers and soldiers sold their IOUs to wealthy speculators, often for a fraction of face value. Hamilton then paid the speculators in full with public money. It was, in this telling, a massive upward redistribution of wealth: the first American bailout. But the assumption also created federal fiscal power, which is the foundation of every progressive program that followed. No federal debt, no federal spending. Hamilton built the engine that would eventually fund the New Deal." },
            { title: "The right-wing case against", desc: "This was the moment centralized federal power was born and became entrenched. Before assumption, the states were sovereign in a meaningful fiscal sense. After it, they were subordinate to a federal government with the power to tax and spend. The states should have been left to handle their own debts, says this narrative. But consolidation also produced the fiscal and monetary stability that fueled American economic growth: sound credit, low taxes (there was no income tax until 1909), and, relative to what came later, genuinely limited government." },
            { title: "The unifying case against", desc: "If you step back from left and right, there is one thing almost everyone can agree to dislike: finance. The assumption of state debts, along with Hamilton's other projects, laid the foundation for the American financial system. Banks. Brokers. Trading. Securities markets. It all traces back, in the United States at least, to the consolidation of state debts into federal bonds and the creation of a market to trade them. To the extent you connect the assumption with the birth of Wall Street, people across the political spectrum can find something to object to." },
          ].map((item, i) => (
            <div key={i} style={{ background: "#FFF", border: "1px solid #EDD5DE", borderRadius: 16, padding: "28px 24px", marginBottom: 16 }}>
              <p style={{ fontSize: 15, fontWeight: 600, color: "#9B1B5A", marginBottom: 8 }}>{item.title}</p>
              <p style={{ fontSize: 15, color: "#555", lineHeight: 1.75, margin: 0 }}>{item.desc}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>

        <h2 style={sectionTitle}>A more honest reading</h2>
        <p style={bodyText}>All of the above is politicized, superficial, and crude. The more honest reading is that the assumption had both good and bad aspects, but that it accomplished a set of goals Hamilton intentionally laid out for the young nation.</p>
        <p style={bodyText}>First, the government should have limited powers, but it should also be financially strong. You do not want a dictatorship, but you also do not want a loose group of largely bankrupt states that cannot defend themselves or enforce contracts. Second, you need rule of law for private enterprise to work. Buying and selling should mean something legally. The assumption established that the United States government honors its obligations, and that precedent still matters. Third, you want the economy to flourish so that many people can flourish. Not only the rich. A financial system helps make that happen, through the provision of credit, through liquidity, and by keeping the economy flexible and dynamic enough to adjust to the many twists and turns of history.</p>
        <p style={bodyText}>Hamilton understood all of this. Whether he got the balance right is the argument Americans have been having for 235 years.</p>

        {/* Two paths for the book */}
        <h2 style={sectionTitle}>Two possible books</h2>
        <div style={{ display: "grid", gridTemplateColumns: "repeat(2, 1fr)", gap: 20, margin: "28px 0" }}>
          <div style={{ background: "#FFF", border: "1px solid #EDD5DE", borderRadius: 20, padding: "32px 24px" }}>
            <div style={{ fontSize: 11, letterSpacing: "2px", textTransform: "uppercase", color: "#C0708A", marginBottom: 12 }}>Path A</div>
            <h3 style={{ fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 20, fontWeight: 400, color: "#3D1028", marginBottom: 12 }}>Historical fiction</h3>
            <p style={{ fontSize: 14.5, color: "#666", lineHeight: 1.7 }}>Two alternating voices. A Connecticut farmer who fought in the war and holds a stack of state IOUs worth, in theory, three years' wages. He needs cash. He sells to a speculator at twelve cents on the dollar. And a young clerk in Hamilton's Treasury office who is drafting the plan that will pay those same IOUs at par, in federal bonds, to whoever holds them now. The farmer's chapters move backward in time through the war and what the debt meant to him. The clerk's chapters move forward through the political fight over assumption, the backroom bargain with Jefferson, and the first days of trading on Wall Street. They never meet. The reader holds both truths at once.</p>
          </div>
          <div style={{ background: "#FFF", border: "1px solid #EDD5DE", borderRadius: 20, padding: "32px 24px" }}>
            <div style={{ fontSize: 11, letterSpacing: "2px", textTransform: "uppercase", color: "#C0708A", marginBottom: 12 }}>Path B</div>
            <h3 style={{ fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 20, fontWeight: 400, color: "#3D1028", marginBottom: 12 }}>Narrative nonfiction</h3>
            <p style={{ fontSize: 14.5, color: "#666", lineHeight: 1.7 }}>A focused, single-event history in the style of "The Big Short" or "When Genius Failed," covering the period from roughly 1789 to 1792. The book would follow the political maneuvering in detail: Hamilton's report, Madison's opposition, the dinner-table compromise, the speculators fanning out to buy up IOUs before news of the plan reached the countryside. It would explain the financial mechanics clearly for a modern reader and draw the line from assumption to the creation of the Bank of New York, the Buttonwood Agreement, and the Panic of 1792. The thesis: everything about American finance, good and bad, starts here.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        {/* Closing */}
        <div style={{ borderLeft: "3px solid #9B1B5A", paddingLeft: 28, marginTop: 48 }}>
          <p style={{ fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 20, color: "#3D1028", lineHeight: 1.5 }}>The assumption is the most important financial event in American history that most Americans have never heard of. It deserves a book that takes it seriously without taking sides.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <ClaudesCorner>The page presents two possible books and they would be genuinely different projects. Path A, the historical fiction, is the harder and more interesting one — the emotional weight comes from two people on opposite sides of the same transaction who never meet. Path B is more commercially legible but risks becoming another Hamilton biography. The competing-narratives section is what makes both worth writing: every modern political tribe can claim this event, and none of them are entirely wrong.</ClaudesCorner>

    </div>
  );
}

function WhichPast({ onBack }) {
  return (
    <div style={{ minHeight: "100vh", background: "#FFFDF6" }}>
      <BackBtn onClick={onBack} />
      <div style={{ maxWidth: 680, margin: "0 auto", padding: "60px 40px 100px" }}>

        <p style={{ fontSize: 11, letterSpacing: "2.5px", textTransform: "uppercase", color: "#C4A84D", marginBottom: 20 }}>Thought</p>
        <h1 style={{ fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 44, fontWeight: 400, color: "#3D2E0A", lineHeight: 1.15, marginBottom: 40 }}>Three Baselines</h1>

        <p style={{ fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 20, color: "#555", lineHeight: 1.8, marginBottom: 40 }}>There are three ways to evaluate the current state of the world.</p>

        <div style={{ margin: "0 0 48px" }}>
          {[
            { num: "1", text: "Against the reality of the past." },
            { num: "2", text: "Against an idealized version of the past." },
            { num: "3", text: "Against an idealized future." },
          ].map((item) => (
            <div key={item.num} style={{ display: "flex", gap: 20, marginBottom: 24, alignItems: "baseline" }}>
              <span style={{ fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 32, color: "#C4A84D", fontWeight: 400, minWidth: 28 }}>{item.num}</span>
              <p style={{ fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 22, color: "#3D2E0A", lineHeight: 1.5, margin: 0 }}>{item.text}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>

        <div style={{ borderTop: "1px solid #EDE5CC", paddingTop: 32 }}>
          <p style={{ fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 17, color: "#888", lineHeight: 1.8 }}>Most disagreements about whether things are getting better or worse are not really about the facts. They are about which baseline someone is using. The nostalgist compares today to a past that never quite existed. The idealist compares today to a future that does not yet exist. The historian compares today to what actually came before. They are all looking at the same present and seeing completely different things.</p>
        </div>

      </div>

      <ClaudesCorner>This is the shortest piece on the site. The idea is a lens, not an argument, and a lens should be simple enough that you can actually remember to use it. I suspect most readers will leave this page and within a week catch themselves mid-argument, realizing they are comparing the present to a past that never quite existed.</ClaudesCorner>

    </div>
  );
}

function Pendulum({ onBack }) {
  const swings = [
    { side: "left", text: "Remote work is obviously better. No commute, more focus, better work-life balance. Why did we ever commute two hours a day to sit in a fluorescent box?" },
    { side: "right", text: "But wait — I'm not actually more focused. I'm distracted at home. And I miss the spontaneous conversations, the energy of being around people. Maybe the office existed for a reason." },
    { side: "left", text: "Then again, the office was mostly performative. Sitting at a desk so your boss could see you sitting at a desk. The meetings that could have been emails. The commute was dead time. Remote work at least respects adults as adults." },
    { side: "right", text: "But junior people are suffering. You can't learn by osmosis over Zoom. Culture doesn't transmit through Slack. And the loneliness is real — not everyone has a rich social life outside of work. The office was, for a lot of people, their community." },
    { side: "left", text: "OK, but forcing everyone back five days a week to solve the loneliness of some people is a blunt instrument. And companies that went fully remote are still functioning. Some are thriving. Maybe the real problem is bad management, not the location." },
    { side: "right", text: "And yet… the companies calling people back seem to be doing fine too. Maybe it doesn't matter as much as either side thinks. Maybe the honest answer is that it depends on the work, the person, and the team, and there is no universal policy that's correct." },
  ];

  return (
    <div style={{ minHeight: "100vh", background: "#F5F9F7" }}>
      <BackBtn onClick={onBack} />
      <div style={{ maxWidth: 680, margin: "0 auto", padding: "60px 40px 100px" }}>

        <p style={{ fontSize: 11, letterSpacing: "2.5px", textTransform: "uppercase", color: "#557A6A", marginBottom: 20 }}>Thought</p>
        <h1 style={{ fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 44, fontWeight: 400, color: "#1A3D2E", lineHeight: 1.15, marginBottom: 24 }}>The Opinion Pendulum</h1>
        <p style={{ fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 19, color: "#777", lineHeight: 1.7, marginBottom: 48 }}>I've noticed a pattern in how I actually form opinions on hard questions. I don't arrive at a view and stay there. I swing — back and forth between opposing positions — but the swings get smaller over time, narrowing toward something I can't quite name yet.</p>

        {/* Pendulum visualization */}
        <div style={{ position: "relative", marginBottom: 48 }}>
          {/* Center line */}
          <div style={{ position: "absolute", left: "50%", top: 0, bottom: 0, width: 1, background: "#D4E0DA" }} />

          {swings.map((swing, i) => {
            const isLeft = swing.side === "left";
            // Narrowing: each swing is less offset than the last
            const maxOffset = 60;
            const offset = maxOffset - (i * 8);
            return (
              <div key={i} style={{ display: "flex", justifyContent: isLeft ? "flex-start" : "flex-end", marginBottom: 20 }}>
                <div style={{
                  maxWidth: `${72 - i * 2}%`,
                  background: "#FFF",
                  border: "1px solid #D4E0DA",
                  borderRadius: 16,
                  padding: "20px 22px",
                  position: "relative",
                }}>
                  <div style={{ position: "absolute", top: 12, [isLeft ? "left" : "right"]: -6, width: 12, height: 12, borderRadius: "50%", background: isLeft ? "#7BAF9A" : "#B8937A" }} />
                  <p style={{ fontSize: 15, color: "#555", lineHeight: 1.7, margin: 0 }}>{swing.text}</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            );
          })}
        </div>

        {/* Reflection */}
        <div style={{ borderTop: "1px solid #D4E0DA", paddingTop: 32 }}>
          <p style={{ fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 17, color: "#888", lineHeight: 1.8, marginBottom: 20 }}>The pendulum never fully stops. But the swings get narrower. Each pass incorporates something from the other side that you can't un-see. You don't end up in the middle, exactly — that would be too convenient. You end up somewhere specific, arrived at through genuine movement, holding contradictions you've decided you can live with.</p>
          <p style={{ fontFamily: "Georgia, serif", fontSize: 17, color: "#888", lineHeight: 1.8 }}>I think this is what honest thinking actually looks like, as opposed to the version we perform publicly, where we pick a side early and defend it. The pendulum is private. It's slow. And the narrowing is the whole point.</p>
        </div>

      </div>
    
      <ClaudesCorner>I notice that I agree with whichever card I am reading, which is either a sign that the writing is working or a sign that I genuinely do not know what I think about remote work. The structure of the piece argues that this confusion is not a failure of reasoning but the early stages of it. I find that more persuasive than I expected to.</ClaudesCorner>
</div>
  );
}

function AudioPlayer({ src, label }) {
  const [playing, setPlaying] = useState(false);
  const [progress, setProgress] = useState(0);
  const audioRef = useRef(null);

  const toggle = () => {
    if (!audioRef.current) return;
    if (playing) { audioRef.current.pause(); } else { audioRef.current.play().catch(() => {}); }
    setPlaying(!playing);
  };

  const onTimeUpdate = () => {
    if (!audioRef.current) return;
    const pct = (audioRef.current.currentTime / audioRef.current.duration) * 100;
    setProgress(pct || 0);
  };

  const onEnded = () => { setPlaying(false); setProgress(0); };

  const seek = (e) => {
    if (!audioRef.current) return;
    const rect = e.currentTarget.getBoundingClientRect();
    const pct = (e.clientX - rect.left) / rect.width;
    audioRef.current.currentTime = pct * audioRef.current.duration;
  };

  return (
    <div style={{ background: "#FFF", border: "1px solid #E8DDD0", borderRadius: 14, padding: "16px 20px", margin: "20px 0 28px", display: "flex", alignItems: "center", gap: 14 }}>
      <audio ref={audioRef} src={src} onTimeUpdate={onTimeUpdate} onEnded={onEnded} preload="metadata" />
      <button onClick={toggle} style={{ width: 36, height: 36, borderRadius: "50%", border: "none", background: "#8B4513", color: "#FFF", cursor: "pointer", fontSize: 14, display: "flex", alignItems: "center", justifyContent: "center", flexShrink: 0 }}>
        {playing ? "❚❚" : "▶"}
      </button>
      <div style={{ flex: 1 }}>
        <p style={{ fontSize: 13, color: "#8B4513", fontWeight: 600, margin: "0 0 6px" }}>{label}</p>
        <div onClick={seek} style={{ height: 4, background: "#EDE5DA", borderRadius: 2, cursor: "pointer", position: "relative" }}>
          <div style={{ height: "100%", background: "#8B4513", borderRadius: 2, width: progress + "%", transition: "width 0.1s" }} />
        </div>
      </div>



    </div>
  );
}

